Research agentic AI / deep research capabilities offered with ServiceNow or Salesforce or that may be planned for the future

We need to understand and forecast how both ServiceNow and Salesforce will stack up against other offerings such as MS 365 Copilot with respect to agentic AI and deep research capable AI in the future

Got it! I will conduct research to analyze and forecast how ServiceNow and Salesforce will compare against offerings like Microsoft 365 Copilot in the realm of agentic AI and deep research capabilities in the future. This will include an overview of current capabilities, announced developments, market trends, and expert opinions on their potential trajectories. I’ll update you as soon as I have the findings.

# Agentic AI in ServiceNow, Salesforce, and Microsoft 365 Copilot: A Comparative Analysis

## Current AI Capabilities 

### ServiceNow 
ServiceNow has gradually infused AI across its workflow automation platform, evolving from basic AI-assisted workflows to **generative and “agentic” AI** capabilities. Its **Now Platform** includes **predictive intelligence** (for ticket routing and anomaly detection) and a **Virtual Agent** chatbot for conversational support. Recently, ServiceNow introduced **Now Assist**, which integrates large language models (LLMs) (via the **Now LLM** and Azure OpenAI) to power features like **chat summarization, case summarization, note generation, code generation, and intelligent search** ([Everything you need to know about ServiceNow GenAI - Plat4mation](https://plat4mation.com/blog/everything-you-need-to-know-about-servicenow-genai/#:~:text=ServiceNow%E2%80%99s%20Now%20Assist%20uses%20the,to%20code%2C%20and%20search%20improvements)) ([Everything you need to know about ServiceNow GenAI - Plat4mation](https://plat4mation.com/blog/everything-you-need-to-know-about-servicenow-genai/#:~:text=ServiceNow%20uses%20the%20power%20of,significantly%20expands%20the%20platform%E2%80%99s%20capabilities)). These assistive features help agents and users quickly find information and generate content within ServiceNow workflows. For example, Now Assist can automatically summarize a customer chat or suggest next steps in an IT support case, reducing manual effort. 

In 2024, ServiceNow began rolling out **autonomous AI agents** that can execute multi-step tasks across its platform. By late 2024, nearly **1,000 enterprise customers** (including early adopters like EY and Rolls-Royce) were using ServiceNow’s AI agents to streamline operations ([ServiceNow adds agentic capabilities, thousands of pre-built AI agents | CIO Dive](https://www.ciodive.com/news/ServiceNow-AI-agent-portfolio-enterprise-automation/738685/#:~:text=ServiceNow%20initially%20introduced%20customers%20to,to%20try%20out%20the%20solutions)) ([Microsoft launches sales-focused AI agents | CIO Dive](https://www.ciodive.com/news/microsoft-sales-ai-agent-copilot/741552/#:~:text=ServiceNow%20announced%20expanded%20capabilities%20to,Royce)). These **agentic AI** capabilities go beyond simple Q&A – the agents can take actions in the platform (e.g. creating tickets, updating records) based on goals set by users. A new **AI Agent Orchestrator** coordinates multiple agents, enabling them to share information and handle complex workflows together ([ServiceNow adds agentic capabilities, thousands of pre-built AI agents | CIO Dive](https://www.ciodive.com/news/ServiceNow-AI-agent-portfolio-enterprise-automation/738685/#:~:text=,cost%2C%20according%20to%20the%20announcement)). In essence, ServiceNow’s current AI offering combines deep workflow automation expertise with generative AI, allowing its virtual agents to not only converse with users but also **perform tasks autonomously** within enterprise processes – a key differentiator in domains like IT service management.

### Salesforce 
Salesforce has embedded AI throughout its Customer 360 platform under the “Einstein” brand for years (e.g. Einstein predictive lead scoring). Its recent leap is **Einstein GPT**, launched in 2023 as “the world’s first generative AI for CRM” ([Salesforce Announces Einstein GPT, the World’s First Generative AI for CRM - Salesforce](https://www.salesforce.com/news/press-releases/2023/03/07/einstein-generative-ai/#:~:text=,research%20tools%2C%20and%20writing%20assistance)) ([Salesforce Announces Einstein GPT, the World’s First Generative AI for CRM - Salesforce](https://www.salesforce.com/news/press-releases/2023/03/07/einstein-generative-ai/#:~:text=San%20Francisco%20%E2%80%94%20March%207%2C,customer%20experience%20with%20generative%20AI)). Einstein GPT and the upgraded **Einstein Copilot** bring generative AI assistance across Salesforce’s clouds – sales, service, marketing, commerce, etc. This means users can ask Salesforce’s AI to draft a sales email, auto-generate a knowledge base article from case notes, write code for a formula, or summarize a customer call transcript. Unlike generic assistants, **Einstein uses an organization’s own CRM data (via Salesforce Data Cloud)** to ground its responses ([Einstein Copilot In-Depth: What It Is, How It Works, and What It Can Do - Salesforce](https://www.salesforce.com/news/stories/about-einstein-copilot/#:~:text=Unlike%20other%20AI%20assistants%20or,requiring%20costly%20AI%20model%20training)) ([Einstein Copilot In-Depth: What It Is, How It Works, and What It Can Do - Salesforce](https://www.salesforce.com/news/stories/about-einstein-copilot/#:~:text=generate%20useful%20responses%2C%20Einstein%20Copilot,requiring%20costly%20AI%20model%20training)). For example, a sales rep can query Einstein Copilot for an account’s recent support cases and get a natural-language summary with relevant details, or a marketer can have it generate personalized campaign copy based on customer segments. These capabilities are bolstered by Salesforce’s **Einstein Trust Layer**, which ensures data governance and integrates **Retrieval Augmented Generation (RAG)** techniques – essentially performing semantic searches on proprietary data and feeding results into the LLM prompt to make answers more accurate and traceable ([How Einstein Copilot Search Uses Retrieval Augmented Generation to Make AI More Trusted and Relevant - Salesforce](https://www.salesforce.com/news/stories/retrieval-augmented-generation-explained/#:~:text=At%20World%20Tour%20NYC%20%2C,through%20the%20Einstein%20Trust%20Layer)) ([How Einstein Copilot Search Uses Retrieval Augmented Generation to Make AI More Trusted and Relevant - Salesforce](https://www.salesforce.com/news/stories/retrieval-augmented-generation-explained/#:~:text=,with%20the%20relevant%20contextual%20data)). This gives Salesforce’s AI a “deep research” ability to pull information from both structured CRM records and unstructured data (emails, call transcripts, knowledge articles) when answering complex questions ([Salesforce introduces Agentforce 2.0, unveils pre-built use cases | CIO Dive](https://www.ciodive.com/news/Salesforce-Agentforce2-agentic-AI-platform/735850/#:~:text=,0%20in%20Slack%20in%20January)) ([How Einstein Copilot Search Uses Retrieval Augmented Generation to Make AI More Trusted and Relevant - Salesforce](https://www.salesforce.com/news/stories/retrieval-augmented-generation-explained/#:~:text=Copilot%2C%20responses%20by%20Large%20Language,through%20the%20Einstein%20Trust%20Layer)). A key differentiator is the tight integration with enterprise data: Salesforce’s AI assistant can **cite the latest customer info and even show sources** for its answers, which builds user trust in contexts like customer support ([How Einstein Copilot Search Uses Retrieval Augmented Generation to Make AI More Trusted and Relevant - Salesforce](https://www.salesforce.com/news/stories/retrieval-augmented-generation-explained/#:~:text=,can%20be%20checked%20for%20accuracy)).

Building on its generative foundation, Salesforce introduced **Agentforce** – an agentic AI platform to create **autonomous AI agents** that act on behalf of users in the CRM context. The current incarnation (Einstein Copilot/Agentforce) is embedded across Salesforce apps and even into Slack (Salesforce’s collaboration tool), allowing conversational interactions like “Find key points from last quarter’s sales calls” or “Update the deal stage for ACME Corp” via natural language ([Einstein Copilot In-Depth: What It Is, How It Works, and What It Can Do - Salesforce](https://www.salesforce.com/news/stories/about-einstein-copilot/#:~:text=Einstein%20Copilot%20is%20natively%20embedded,customer%20relationships%2C%20and%20higher%20margins)) ([Einstein Copilot In-Depth: What It Is, How It Works, and What It Can Do - Salesforce](https://www.salesforce.com/news/stories/about-einstein-copilot/#:~:text=For%20example%2C%20using%20simple%20natural,and%20quickly%20generate%20personalized%20promotions)). These agents can dynamically chain actions: for instance, look up a product in a knowledge base, then draft a tailored reply to a customer, and log the interaction – all in one prompt. Salesforce’s focus today is on **proactive AI assistance**. As one Salesforce AI executive put it, the goal is **“agents that can take action… Not like copilots that are reactive, but agents that can be proactive.”** ([Salesforce introduces Agentforce 2.0, unveils pre-built use cases | CIO Dive](https://www.ciodive.com/news/Salesforce-Agentforce2-agentic-AI-platform/735850/#:~:text=%E2%80%9CWhat%20we%20need%20to%20really,%E2%80%9D)). This emphasis on action-oriented AI in CRM and customer service scenarios differentiates Salesforce’s approach – the AI not only generates content but also executes transactions (like updating records or scheduling follow-ups) to drive productivity.

### Microsoft 365 Copilot 
Microsoft 365 Copilot serves as Microsoft’s generative AI assistant for knowledge workers, embedded in the Office 365 suite and related Microsoft apps. Launched in 2023, Copilot can generate and summarize content across **Word, Excel, PowerPoint, Outlook, Teams, and more** ([Microsoft readies Copilot Studio for agentic AI | CIO Dive](https://www.ciodive.com/news/Microsoft-Copilot-Studio-AI-agents-Ignite-conference/733352/#:~:text=SAP%20%2C%20%2025%2C%20Slack,in%20Copilot%20Studio%20in%20November)) ([Introducing Copilot agents - Microsoft Support](https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/topic/introducing-copilot-agents-943e563d-602d-40fa-bdd1-dbc83f582466#:~:text=Copilot%C2%A0agents%20are%20specialized%20AI%20assistants,expanding%20their%20reach%20and%20functionality)). For example, users can ask Copilot in Word to draft a document on a given topic, have it create an Excel formula or analyze spreadsheet data, summarize long email threads in Outlook, or even generate a PowerPoint deck from a Word outline. Copilot leverages **OpenAI’s GPT-4 model augmented with Microsoft Graph data** (the user’s emails, calendar, files, Teams chats, etc.) to provide contextually relevant outputs ([Microsoft 365 Copilot overview](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/copilot/microsoft-365/microsoft-365-copilot-overview#:~:text=Microsoft%20365%20Copilot%20overview%20Microsoft,of%20Microsoft%20Graph%20data%2C)) ([A Look Inside Microsoft Copilot's RAG System - Zenity Labs](https://labs.zenity.io/p/a-look-inside-copilot-rag-system#:~:text=Microsoft%20Copilot%27s%20real%20superpower%20is,your%20documents%2C%20emails%20and%20messages)). This means it has a “personalized knowledge base” – if you ask “Summarize the recent meeting with Client X,” it can pull details from meeting transcripts or notes in Teams and produce an answer. Microsoft also introduced a **Business Chat** mode, which allows a user to query across all their work data at once (e.g. “What are the biggest risks in our Q4 project?”) and get an answer synthesized from emails, SharePoint documents, and meeting notes ([Semantic indexing for Microsoft 365 Copilot](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/microsoftsearch/semantic-index-for-copilot#:~:text=Semantic%20index%20is%20generated%20from,relevant%20responses%20to%20user%20queries)) ([Microsoft 365 Copilot overview](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/copilot/microsoft-365/microsoft-365-copilot-overview#:~:text=lexical%20and%20semantic%20understanding%20of,Microsoft%20Graph%20data%2C)). 

Where Microsoft is expanding towards agentic AI is with **Copilot Agents and Copilot Studio**. Copilot Agents are specialized AI assistants that connect to organizational systems and data beyond the Microsoft 365 apps ([Introducing Copilot agents - Microsoft Support](https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/topic/introducing-copilot-agents-943e563d-602d-40fa-bdd1-dbc83f582466#:~:text=Copilot%C2%A0agents%20are%20specialized%20AI%20assistants,expanding%20their%20reach%20and%20functionality)). They can automate multi-step tasks like updating CRM entries or pulling data from third-party databases, effectively turning Copilot into a platform for workflow agents. For instance, Microsoft has demonstrated a **Sales Copilot** that integrates with Dynamics 365 CRM and even Salesforce CRM to autonomously **research sales leads, schedule meetings, and draft outreach emails** using both internal data and internet research ([Microsoft launches sales-focused AI agents | CIO Dive](https://www.ciodive.com/news/microsoft-sales-ai-agent-copilot/741552/#:~:text=,the%20agents%20to%20get%20more)) ([Microsoft launches sales-focused AI agents | CIO Dive](https://www.ciodive.com/news/microsoft-sales-ai-agent-copilot/741552/#:~:text=,more%20accurate%20and%20actionable%20responses)). Currently, Microsoft 365 Copilot’s strength is in **productivity and “knowledge work” tasks** – it acts as a cognitive assistant that users work *with* (hence “copilot”). Its key differentiators include the breadth of applications it touches (from documents to spreadsheets to meetings) and Microsoft’s investment in enterprise-ready AI controls (privacy, security, compliance built-in via Azure OpenAI and Microsoft Graph). While traditionally Copilot was more user-driven (responding to user prompts within Office apps), Microsoft is rapidly adding **agentic capabilities** such as allowing Copilot to **execute scripted actions and connect to external workflows**. In short, today’s Microsoft 365 Copilot helps users draft, analyze, and synthesize information across their work tools, and is beginning to evolve into an orchestrator of tasks across enterprise systems.

## Announced and Roadmapped AI Developments 

### ServiceNow 
ServiceNow has made **agentic AI a strategic focus** in its roadmap, with several notable announcements in late 2024 and early 2025 aimed at accelerating autonomous workflow automation. In January 2025, ServiceNow unveiled plans to launch an **AI Agent Orchestrator** and **thousands of pre-built AI agents** in its upcoming platform release ([ServiceNow adds agentic capabilities, thousands of pre-built AI agents | CIO Dive](https://www.ciodive.com/news/ServiceNow-AI-agent-portfolio-enterprise-automation/738685/#:~:text=,where%20customers%20can%20tailor%20solutions)). The **AI Agent Orchestrator** (live as of March 2025 for Enterprise Plus customers) is designed to coordinate multiple AI agents, improving communication and information sharing between them in complex workflows ([ServiceNow adds agentic capabilities, thousands of pre-built AI agents | CIO Dive](https://www.ciodive.com/news/ServiceNow-AI-agent-portfolio-enterprise-automation/738685/#:~:text=,cost%2C%20according%20to%20the%20announcement)). Alongside this, a new **AI Agent Studio** (part of the *“Yokohama”* platform release) provides a **no-code/low-code environment** for customers to create and tailor their own agents ([ServiceNow adds agentic capabilities, thousands of pre-built AI agents | CIO Dive](https://www.ciodive.com/news/ServiceNow-AI-agent-portfolio-enterprise-automation/738685/#:~:text=,where%20customers%20can%20tailor%20solutions)) ([ServiceNow releases no-code, low-code AI agent builder | CIO Dive](https://www.ciodive.com/news/servicenow-yokohama-agentic-ai-low-code-development-tool/742275/#:~:text=,a%20%2025%20series%20of)). This studio centralizes agent development with built-in workflow approvals and change management, making it easier for organizations to build custom agents without deep AI expertise ([ServiceNow releases no-code, low-code AI agent builder | CIO Dive](https://www.ciodive.com/news/servicenow-yokohama-agentic-ai-low-code-development-tool/742275/#:~:text=,a%20%2025%20series%20of)). By moving these tools to general availability, ServiceNow is clearly lowering the barrier for enterprises to adopt AI agents at scale.

ServiceNow is also **investing heavily via acquisitions** to enrich its AI capabilities. In Q1 2025, it announced the acquisition of **Cuein**, a conversational AI and data analysis platform, and a blockbuster **$2.85 billion deal for Moveworks**, an AI software vendor known for its conversational enterprise assistant ([ServiceNow agentic AI acquisitions set pace for enterprises | TechTarget](https://www.techtarget.com/searchitoperations/news/366620527/ServiceNow-agentic-AI-acquisitions-set-pace-for-enterprises#:~:text=On%20Jan,largest%20acquisition%20in%20ServiceNow%27s%20history)). Moveworks is ServiceNow’s largest acquisition ever and is significant for two reasons: First, Moveworks brings advanced **natural language enterprise search** and conversational AI that can plug into ServiceNow’s workflows ([ServiceNow agentic AI acquisitions set pace for enterprises | TechTarget](https://www.techtarget.com/searchitoperations/news/366620527/ServiceNow-agentic-AI-acquisitions-set-pace-for-enterprises#:~:text=Moveworks%20also%20brings%20AI,18%20months%2C%20according%20to%20ServiceNow)). This boosts the “deep research” capability of ServiceNow’s agents – for example, an AI agent can search across company knowledge bases or intranet content to answer an employee question or troubleshoot an IT issue, using Moveworks’ search prowess. Second, Moveworks adds a team of 500 AI experts and a platform proven to support millions of users ([ServiceNow agentic AI acquisitions set pace for enterprises | TechTarget](https://www.techtarget.com/searchitoperations/news/366620527/ServiceNow-agentic-AI-acquisitions-set-pace-for-enterprises#:~:text=Moveworks%20also%20brings%20AI,18%20months%2C%20according%20to%20ServiceNow)). ServiceNow’s leadership frames these moves as **“giant leaps forward”** in its shift from traditional automation to autonomous agents ([ServiceNow releases no-code, low-code AI agent builder | CIO Dive](https://www.ciodive.com/news/servicenow-yokohama-agentic-ai-low-code-development-tool/742275/#:~:text=Acquisitions%20are%20also%20helping%20vendors,agents%2C%20according%20to%20the%20announcement)). The AI Agent Orchestrator (released Jan 29, 2025) plus the new acquisitions set the stage for “the next major evolution of AI” in IT operations, according to analysts ([ServiceNow agentic AI acquisitions set pace for enterprises | TechTarget](https://www.techtarget.com/searchitoperations/news/366620527/ServiceNow-agentic-AI-acquisitions-set-pace-for-enterprises#:~:text=With%20these%20moves%20and%20the,an%20analyst%20at%20Constellation%20Research)). In practical terms, the roadmap suggests ServiceNow will soon offer **out-of-the-box agent libraries** (e.g. pre-built IT support agents, HR agents, security agents) and tighter integration of conversational intelligence (via Cuein) to allow agents to better understand and even **proactively optimize workflows** by analyzing conversation data ([HOT TAKE: ServiceNow Hits the Gas on Agentic AI Roadmap with Cuein AI Pick Up | Constellation Research Inc.](https://www.constellationr.com/blog-news/hot-take-servicenow-hits-gas-agentic-ai-roadmap-cuein-ai-pick#:~:text=What%20happens%20when%20the%20%E2%80%9CPlatform,the%20press%20release%C2%A0and%20Insights%20coverage)) ([HOT TAKE: ServiceNow Hits the Gas on Agentic AI Roadmap with Cuein AI Pick Up | Constellation Research Inc.](https://www.constellationr.com/blog-news/hot-take-servicenow-hits-gas-agentic-ai-roadmap-cuein-ai-pick#:~:text=What%20makes%20Cuein%20AI%20so,to%20work%20to%20infer%20customer)). We can expect ServiceNow to continue enhancing multi-agent orchestration, domain-specific intelligence (ITSM, security operations, etc.), and governance features, aiming to maintain its lead in enterprise workflow automation as it infuses more AI. 

### Salesforce 
Salesforce’s AI roadmap has accelerated with a flurry of announcements around its Einstein platform and the new Agentforce initiative. In early 2023, Salesforce kicked off with **Einstein GPT**, integrating OpenAI’s technology to bring generative AI natively into CRM (and even launched a ChatGPT app for Slack) ([Salesforce Announces Einstein GPT, the World’s First Generative AI for CRM - Salesforce](https://www.salesforce.com/news/press-releases/2023/03/07/einstein-generative-ai/#:~:text=experience%20better%20,development%20of%20responsible%20generative%20AI)) ([Salesforce Announces Einstein GPT, the World’s First Generative AI for CRM - Salesforce](https://www.salesforce.com/news/press-releases/2023/03/07/einstein-generative-ai/#:~:text=out,development%20of%20responsible%20generative%20AI)). By late 2023 and into 2024, Salesforce expanded this into a comprehensive **AI Cloud** offering: they introduced the **Einstein Trust Layer** for secure AI usage, allowed integration of **multiple AI models** (including Anthropic’s Claude and other models via Amazon Bedrock) ([Salesforce Announces Einstein GPT, the World’s First Generative AI for CRM - Salesforce](https://www.salesforce.com/news/press-releases/2023/03/07/einstein-generative-ai/#:~:text=Einstein%20GPT%20will%20infuse%20Salesforce%E2%80%99s,and%20needs%20in%20real%20time)) ([Salesforce Data Cloud Spring '24 Release Sets New Standards in ...](https://www.bigdatawire.com/this-just-in/salesforce-data-cloud-spring-24-release-sets-new-standards-in-combating-data-fragmentation-with-ai-insights/#:~:text=Salesforce%20Data%20Cloud%20Spring%20%2724,SageMaker%2C%20Anthropic%2C%20Cohere%2C%20Databricks%2C)), and most visibly, unveiled **Einstein Copilot** – a conversational UI for users to interact with AI across Salesforce apps. An important evolution came with **Agentforce** in H2 2024. **Agentforce 1.0** was Salesforce’s first take on an agentic AI platform, and just a few months later, **Agentforce 2.0** was announced (December 2024) with significant enhancements ([Salesforce introduces Agentforce 2.0, unveils pre-built use cases | CIO Dive](https://www.ciodive.com/news/Salesforce-Agentforce2-agentic-AI-platform/735850/#:~:text=Salesforce%20introduces%20Agentforce%202,built%20use%20cases)) ([Salesforce introduces Agentforce 2.0, unveils pre-built use cases | CIO Dive](https://www.ciodive.com/news/Salesforce-Agentforce2-agentic-AI-platform/735850/#:~:text=,0%20in%20Slack%20in)). Agentforce 2.0, which enters general availability in Feb 2025, includes a **library of pre-built agent skills and workflow integrations**, and **enhanced reasoning and data retrieval capabilities** so that agents can handle more complex, multi-step queries ([Salesforce introduces Agentforce 2.0, unveils pre-built use cases | CIO Dive](https://www.ciodive.com/news/Salesforce-Agentforce2-agentic-AI-platform/735850/#:~:text=,0%20in%20Slack%20in%20January)). Early adopters of Agentforce (Accenture, IBM, Indeed) have been trialing these autonomous agents in contexts like consulting and HR, indicating Salesforce’s push beyond CRM into broader enterprise use cases ([Salesforce introduces Agentforce 2.0, unveils pre-built use cases | CIO Dive](https://www.ciodive.com/news/Salesforce-Agentforce2-agentic-AI-platform/735850/#:~:text=,0%20in%20Slack%20in%20January)).

Salesforce’s roadmap emphasizes **embedding agents in the flow of work for employees and customers**. For instance, customers will be able to deploy Salesforce’s AI agents into **Slack in January 2025** ([Salesforce introduces Agentforce 2.0, unveils pre-built use cases | CIO Dive](https://www.ciodive.com/news/Salesforce-Agentforce2-agentic-AI-platform/735850/#:~:text=capabilities%20allowing%20agents%20to%20respond,0%20in%20Slack%20in%20January)), meaning a sales manager could chat with an “Einstein agent” in Slack to update a pipeline or get a briefing, blurring the line between collaboration and CRM systems. Salesforce is also investing in scale and enablement: CEO Marc Benioff noted that the company closed **200+ Agentforce deals in one week** (with thousands more in the pipeline) and is hiring **2,000 sales staff** to sell AI solutions ([Salesforce introduces Agentforce 2.0, unveils pre-built use cases | CIO Dive](https://www.ciodive.com/news/Salesforce-Agentforce2-agentic-AI-platform/735850/#:~:text=to%20a%20July%20Capgemini%20survey)). This aggressive go-to-market effort is part of Salesforce’s strategy to position **Agentforce as a leading platform for “digital workforces”** – essentially teams of AI agents that augment human workers ([Salesforce introduces Agentforce 2.0, unveils pre-built use cases | CIO Dive](https://www.ciodive.com/news/Salesforce-Agentforce2-agentic-AI-platform/735850/#:~:text=While%20organizations%20are%20still%20grappling,to%20a%20July%20Capgemini%20survey)). 

On the technical front, Salesforce is advancing its **Data Cloud** to feed these AI agents richer data (now including unstructured data storage and semantic search as of mid-2024) ([How Einstein Copilot Search Uses Retrieval Augmented Generation to Make AI More Trusted and Relevant - Salesforce](https://www.salesforce.com/news/stories/retrieval-augmented-generation-explained/#:~:text=safe%20and%20secure%20through%20the,Einstein%20Trust%20Layer)) ([How Einstein Copilot Search Uses Retrieval Augmented Generation to Make AI More Trusted and Relevant - Salesforce](https://www.salesforce.com/news/stories/retrieval-augmented-generation-explained/#:~:text=ImageEinstein%20Copilot%20Search%20enables%20patterns,AI%20more%20trusted%20and%20relevant)). The combination of Agentforce + Data Cloud means future Salesforce agents could not only act (e.g. update a case or send an email) but also **research and reason** over a company’s entire customer dataset before acting. Officially announced upcoming features include deeper **integration of AI into workflow automation (Flows)** and industry-specific AI models. Salesforce has hinted at *“auto-pilot” workflows where agents trigger business processes proactively*. For example, an agent might detect from customer sentiment data that a VIP client is unhappy and automatically initiate a retention workflow. While not all such capabilities are live yet, Salesforce’s roadmap clearly points toward **proactive, autonomous CRM agents**. In sum, expect Salesforce to continue blending its generative AI (Einstein GPT) with autonomous agents (Agentforce) – differentiating via its customer data specialization and a promise of trusted, enterprise-safe AI. Notably, Salesforce leaders contrast their approach with others by saying copilots are not enough; their focus is on **agents “that can be proactive” to truly boost productivity** ([Salesforce introduces Agentforce 2.0, unveils pre-built use cases | CIO Dive](https://www.ciodive.com/news/Salesforce-Agentforce2-agentic-AI-platform/735850/#:~:text=%E2%80%9CWhat%20we%20need%20to%20really,%E2%80%9D)).

### Microsoft 365 Copilot 
Microsoft’s announced AI developments indicate that Copilot is evolving from a productivity assistant into a broader **platform for building AI agents**, underpinned by ongoing investments in security and infrastructure. At Microsoft’s Ignite conference in late 2024, the company announced an expanded **Copilot Studio**, which allows organizations to **create, tune, and deploy custom Copilot agents** ([Microsoft readies Copilot Studio for agentic AI | CIO Dive](https://www.ciodive.com/news/Microsoft-Copilot-Studio-AI-agents-Ignite-conference/733352/#:~:text=,with%20comprehensive%20enterprise%20data%20protection)). These agents can connect to specific knowledge sources – Microsoft upgraded Copilot Studio’s ability to plug into enterprise databases and customize an agent’s grounding data ([Microsoft readies Copilot Studio for agentic AI | CIO Dive](https://www.ciodive.com/news/Microsoft-Copilot-Studio-AI-agents-Ignite-conference/733352/#:~:text=,image%20analysis%20among%20other%20enhancements)). Significantly, **autonomous AI agents in Copilot Studio entered public preview** in late 2024 ([Microsoft readies Copilot Studio for agentic AI | CIO Dive](https://www.ciodive.com/news/Microsoft-Copilot-Studio-AI-agents-Ignite-conference/733352/#:~:text=,image%20analysis%20among%20other%20enhancements)). Microsoft also introduced **multimodal capabilities** for Copilot agents – meaning agents can accept voice commands or analyze images as part of their input/output ([Microsoft readies Copilot Studio for agentic AI | CIO Dive](https://www.ciodive.com/news/Microsoft-Copilot-Studio-AI-agents-Ignite-conference/733352/#:~:text=,AI%20strategy%20to%20address%20risks)). For example, a user could speak a request to an agent or an agent could process an image (perhaps reading a screenshot or chart to answer a query). These roadmap enhancements aim to make Copilot agents more versatile and easier to build. Early feedback has been strong – in fact, over a three-month period, organizations built **more than 400,000 custom agents in Copilot Studio** (in preview) ([Microsoft launches sales-focused AI agents | CIO Dive](https://www.ciodive.com/news/microsoft-sales-ai-agent-copilot/741552/#:~:text=The%20Microsoft%20headquarters%20on%20July,Ryder%2FGetty%20Images%20via%20Getty%20Images)), indicating substantial interest in Microsoft’s AI extensibility.

Microsoft has also rolled out **domain-specific Copilots and agents** as part of its strategy. In 2023-2024 it announced Copilots for **Dynamics 365 (enterprise apps)**, **Power Platform (low-code development)**, **Security Copilot**, and even **Windows Copilot** – showing a roadmap to infuse AI assistance across its entire ecosystem. In March 2025, Microsoft introduced **two new AI agents for Sales**, aptly named **Sales Agent** and **Sales Chat**, which integrate with Dynamics 365 Sales *and even rival CRM systems like Salesforce* ([Microsoft launches sales-focused AI agents | CIO Dive](https://www.ciodive.com/news/microsoft-sales-ai-agent-copilot/741552/#:~:text=,the%20agents%20to%20get%20more)) ([Microsoft launches sales-focused AI agents | CIO Dive](https://www.ciodive.com/news/microsoft-sales-ai-agent-copilot/741552/#:~:text=,more%20accurate%20and%20actionable%20responses)). Sales Agent is particularly notable: it can **autonomously perform sales tasks** – finding leads, researching them on the internet, updating the CRM, and contacting prospects – essentially acting as a junior sales rep that works 24/7 on prospecting ([Microsoft launches sales-focused AI agents | CIO Dive](https://www.ciodive.com/news/microsoft-sales-ai-agent-copilot/741552/#:~:text=,more%20accurate%20and%20actionable%20responses)). These new agents will be accessible via Microsoft 365 Copilot and a Chat interface by May 2025 (in preview), and organizations can fine-tune them for better accuracy ([Microsoft launches sales-focused AI agents | CIO Dive](https://www.ciodive.com/news/microsoft-sales-ai-agent-copilot/741552/#:~:text=autonomously%20researches%20leads%2C%20sets%20up,more%20accurate%20and%20actionable%20responses)). This indicates Microsoft’s roadmap is not limited to Office productivity; it’s leveraging Copilot’s framework to deliver AI helpers in business workflows (sales, customer service, etc.), directly competing in areas traditionally dominated by companies like Salesforce.

On the “deep research” and data side, Microsoft is enhancing how Copilot accesses enterprise knowledge. **Semantic Index for Copilot** (announced mid-2023) automatically indexes an organization’s Microsoft 365 data to improve retrieval of relevant content ([Semantic indexing for Microsoft 365 Copilot](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/microsoftsearch/semantic-index-for-copilot#:~:text=Semantic%20index%20is%20generated%20from,relevant%20responses%20to%20user%20queries)). Additionally, Microsoft supports connectors and plugins to bring **external data** into Copilot’s purview ([How Microsoft 365 Copilot can work with your external data](https://officegarageitpro.medium.com/how-microsoft-365-copilot-can-work-with-your-external-data-443a665c670c#:~:text=data%20officegarageitpro,way%20integration%20using%20plugins)). For instance, through the Microsoft Graph connectors, Copilot could query an external knowledge base or database on-premises. Microsoft’s roadmap emphasizes **responsible AI and security** as well – at Ignite, it unveiled new data protection features for agents (encryption, DLP, prompt injection safeguards) ([Microsoft readies Copilot Studio for agentic AI | CIO Dive](https://www.ciodive.com/news/Microsoft-Copilot-Studio-AI-agents-Ignite-conference/733352/#:~:text=enhancements.%20,AI%20strategy%20to%20address%20risks)). This was in direct response to enterprise concerns about autonomous AI, positioning Microsoft 365 Copilot as a solution with “comprehensive enterprise data protection” for any AI agent built on it ([Microsoft readies Copilot Studio for agentic AI | CIO Dive](https://www.ciodive.com/news/Microsoft-Copilot-Studio-AI-agents-Ignite-conference/733352/#:~:text=Copilot%20Studio%20are%20currently%20in,like%20prompt%20injection%2C%E2%80%9D%20Microsoft%20said)). We can expect Microsoft to continue rapidly adding new Copilot features on a monthly cadence (aligning with Microsoft 365 updates). In the near future, Microsoft 365 Copilot will likely become more deeply integrated into business workflows (via Teams and Viva apps), gain improved ability to take actions in third-party applications, and benefit from Microsoft’s investments in AI infrastructure (e.g. specialized Azure AI chips to speed up agentic workloads ([Microsoft readies Copilot Studio for agentic AI | CIO Dive](https://www.ciodive.com/news/Microsoft-Copilot-Studio-AI-agents-Ignite-conference/733352/#:~:text=Infusing%20agentic%20AI%20throughout%20operations,to%20meet%20the%20new%20requirements)) ([Microsoft readies Copilot Studio for agentic AI | CIO Dive](https://www.ciodive.com/news/Microsoft-Copilot-Studio-AI-agents-Ignite-conference/733352/#:~:text=Microsoft%20unveiled%20customized%20chips%20Tuesday,cloud%20infrastructure%2C%20the%20company%20said))). 

In summary, all three companies have robust AI roadmaps: ServiceNow doubling down on workflow agents and acquisitions, Salesforce unifying generative AI with autonomous agents for CRM, and Microsoft expanding Copilot from an Office assistant to a general platform for enterprise AI agents. Each is **rapidly shipping new AI features** and improvements, signaling an intensifying race to capture enterprise AI leadership. 

## Competitive Positioning 

The competition in AI-powered enterprise platforms is fierce, with **ServiceNow, Salesforce, and Microsoft each leveraging their unique strengths**:

- **ServiceNow** currently differentiates by **deep workflow and IT process automation** expertise. It’s a platform widely used for IT service management, HR, and operations, and by integrating agentic AI, ServiceNow is turning those workflows autonomous. It was already a leader in automating and tracking business/IT workflows (ranked #1 in market share for ITSM/AIOps by Gartner) ([ServiceNow agentic AI acquisitions set pace for enterprises | TechTarget](https://www.techtarget.com/searchitoperations/news/366620527/ServiceNow-agentic-AI-acquisitions-set-pace-for-enterprises#:~:text=ServiceNow%20first%20launched%20an%20AI,management%20and%20software%20asset%20management)). Now, with AI agents, ServiceNow is positioning itself as the go-to for complex **back-office and operational AI agents** (e.g. an agent that can detect an incident, open a ticket, remediate the issue, and update stakeholders automatically). Its recent acquisitions (Moveworks, Cuein) hint at a strategy to offer **out-of-the-box solutions** – rather than expecting customers to build from scratch, ServiceNow can bundle pre-built agents for common use cases (like an employee self-service helpdesk agent). This could be a competitive edge against more general platforms; for example, a ServiceNow agent might natively understand ITSM data and processes better than a generalized Microsoft agent. However, ServiceNow faces the challenge of being perceived as an IT-centric tool – it is expanding into other enterprise functions, but Salesforce and Microsoft have broader user bases. Still, analysts note that in regulated industries or any environment with heavy workflow governance, **“ServiceNow is a leader”** due to its robust process controls ([ServiceNow agentic AI acquisitions set pace for enterprises | TechTarget](https://www.techtarget.com/searchitoperations/news/366620527/ServiceNow-agentic-AI-acquisitions-set-pace-for-enterprises#:~:text=Still%2C%20,Thurai%20said)). As agentic AI adoption grows, ServiceNow’s long history in automation gives it credibility, though its solutions can be **pricey and complex** for some customers ([ServiceNow agentic AI acquisitions set pace for enterprises | TechTarget](https://www.techtarget.com/searchitoperations/news/366620527/ServiceNow-agentic-AI-acquisitions-set-pace-for-enterprises#:~:text=ServiceNow%20has%20poured%20ample%20R%26D,at%20times%20required%20complex%20configurations)). 

- **Salesforce** has a competitive edge through its **customer-centric data and CRM dominance**. With Salesforce’s Einstein GPT and Copilot already embedded in sales, service, and marketing workflows, its AI is deeply aware of customer context – something neither ServiceNow nor Microsoft match directly (they excel in other areas). Salesforce is positioning Agentforce as the platform for **“digital labor” in customer-facing roles** ([Salesforce introduces Agentforce 2.0, unveils pre-built use cases | CIO Dive](https://www.ciodive.com/news/Salesforce-Agentforce2-agentic-AI-platform/735850/#:~:text=Benioff%20said%20during%20the%20event,Tuesday)). This means a company could rely on Salesforce’s agents to handle a significant portion of customer interactions, sales outreach, and support queries autonomously. In competitive terms, Salesforce pitches this as a step beyond what a “copilot” (read: Microsoft’s Copilot) can do, emphasizing **action-taking agents vs. passive assistants** ([Salesforce introduces Agentforce 2.0, unveils pre-built use cases | CIO Dive](https://www.ciodive.com/news/Salesforce-Agentforce2-agentic-AI-platform/735850/#:~:text=%E2%80%9CWhat%20we%20need%20to%20really,%E2%80%9D)). Additionally, Salesforce’s ecosystem (Tableau for analytics, MuleSoft for integration, Slack for collaboration) all tie into its AI strategy, potentially offering a more unified front-end for enterprise users. For example, a support agent in Slack can interact with a Salesforce AI agent that pulls data via MuleSoft from an external ERP – a scenario playing to Salesforce’s integrated stack. Against Microsoft 365 Copilot, Salesforce might seem narrower (focused on CRM and customer processes), but it competes by claiming domain depth and trusted usage of *your* company’s data. And while Microsoft has a massive productivity footprint, many organizations’ **mission-critical customer data sits in Salesforce** – giving Salesforce a strong incumbent advantage to infuse AI right where that data lives. When comparing Salesforce and ServiceNow, there is some overlap (both want to automate workflows with AI agents), but often they serve different parts of the business: Salesforce in front-office (sales, marketing, service) and ServiceNow in back-office (IT operations, internal workflows). It’s worth noting Salesforce has also rapidly partnered or invested in AI startups (Anthropic, Cohere, etc.) to ensure it can offer model flexibility and keep up with any cutting-edge developments ([Salesforce Announces Einstein GPT, the World’s First Generative AI for CRM - Salesforce](https://www.salesforce.com/news/press-releases/2023/03/07/einstein-generative-ai/#:~:text=Einstein%20GPT%20will%20infuse%20Salesforce%E2%80%99s,and%20needs%20in%20real%20time)) ([Salesforce Data Cloud Spring '24 Release Sets New Standards in ...](https://www.bigdatawire.com/this-just-in/salesforce-data-cloud-spring-24-release-sets-new-standards-in-combating-data-fragmentation-with-ai-insights/#:~:text=Salesforce%20Data%20Cloud%20Spring%20%2724,SageMaker%2C%20Anthropic%2C%20Cohere%2C%20Databricks%2C)). In the big picture, Salesforce is very aggressively marketing its AI – even running Super Bowl ads featuring its Agentforce – to stake a claim as the **top AI platform for enterprise productivity** ([Why is There So Much Hype Around AI Agents in 2025? - InnoLead](https://www.innovationleader.com/topics/articles-and-content-by-topic/scouting-trends-and-tech/why-is-there-so-much-hype-around-agentic-ai-2025/#:~:text=One%20ad%20in%20particular%20was,miss%20your%20flight%20to%20the)) ([Why is There So Much Hype Around AI Agents in 2025? - InnoLead](https://www.innovationleader.com/topics/articles-and-content-by-topic/scouting-trends-and-tech/why-is-there-so-much-hype-around-agentic-ai-2025/#:~:text=Taking%20the%20big%20consultancies%E2%80%99%20perspective,of%20their%20companies%E2%80%99%20AI%20transformation)).

- **Microsoft 365 Copilot** holds an advantage as a **ubiquitous productivity platform** – Microsoft can embed AI in tools that hundreds of millions use daily (Outlook, Word, Teams, etc.). In the short term, this has made Copilot something of a standard for AI-assisted productivity; competitors have even adopted the “copilot” moniker in response. Microsoft’s integration of Copilot with its **entire suite (Office, Teams, Dynamics, Power Platform, GitHub, etc.)** gives it a breadth that Salesforce and ServiceNow individually don’t match. For instance, Microsoft can claim a cohesive AI experience from writing code (GitHub Copilot) to analyzing business data (Power BI with AI) to drafting a legal contract (Word) – covering a spectrum of general knowledge work tasks. Moreover, Microsoft’s massive investment in OpenAI (and access to advanced models like GPT-4) provided an early lead in generative AI quality. That said, Microsoft is now going beyond content generation into **agentic functionality** to keep pace with the “agent” trend that Salesforce and ServiceNow are riding. The introduction of Copilot Studio and specialized agents (like the Sales Agent that can tap into Salesforce data) shows Microsoft **competing on multiple fronts** – not just in Office productivity, but also in CRM and potentially IT workflows (via connectors to other systems). This cross-domain approach could be powerful: Microsoft’s sales-focused agents, for example, challenge Salesforce on its home turf by offering an AI helper that works across Outlook (email outreach), Teams (meetings), and even a Salesforce CRM system simultaneously ([Microsoft launches sales-focused AI agents | CIO Dive](https://www.ciodive.com/news/microsoft-sales-ai-agent-copilot/741552/#:~:text=,the%20agents%20to%20get%20more)) ([Microsoft launches sales-focused AI agents | CIO Dive](https://www.ciodive.com/news/microsoft-sales-ai-agent-copilot/741552/#:~:text=,more%20accurate%20and%20actionable%20responses)). Microsoft’s competitive positioning is to be the **platform-of-platforms for AI** – if it can integrate with everyone’s data (through Microsoft Graph and connectors) and still deliver a seamless user experience in Microsoft 365, it can insert itself as the primary AI interface for workers. One challenge for Microsoft is that while it is everywhere, it must prove its AI is as *specialized* or trustworthy in specific domains as rivals. For example, will a customer support team prefer Microsoft Copilot over Salesforce’s Einstein, which is tuned to customer service workflows? Microsoft is trying to address that by allowing fine-tuning of its agents and by working with partners (the Sales Agent implicitly acknowledges many sales teams use Salesforce CRM alongside Microsoft tools) ([Microsoft launches sales-focused AI agents | CIO Dive](https://www.ciodive.com/news/microsoft-sales-ai-agent-copilot/741552/#:~:text=,the%20agents%20to%20get%20more)). 

Beyond these three, the enterprise AI landscape includes **other emerging players** that influence competitive positioning. **Google** has launched **Duet AI for Workspace** (bringing similar generative features to Google Docs/Gmail and also building AI into Google Cloud services) – an alternative for companies in the Google ecosystem. **SAP** introduced **SAP Joule**, an AI assistant for its ERP cloud, signaling that even specialized enterprise software like finance and supply chain will have built-in AI copilots. **IBM** is pushing its **Watsonx** platform for enterprises to develop their own AI solutions (often emphasizing data privacy and industry-tuned models). **AWS** offers Bedrock and CodeWhisperer, and has been rapidly adding AI features that could be components of agentic solutions (though AWS often partners with enterprise software vendors rather than directly competing with an end-user assistant). There are also **smaller innovators** and startups – as of late 2024, Forrester identified *around 400 vendors* offering some form of AI agent platform ([ServiceNow adds agentic capabilities, thousands of pre-built AI agents | CIO Dive](https://www.ciodive.com/news/ServiceNow-AI-agent-portfolio-enterprise-automation/738685/#:~:text=Salesforce%20is%20adding%202%2C000%20sales,the%20degree%20of%20autonomy%20varies)). This ranges from vertical-specific agents (for customer support, HR, finance) to more general agent frameworks. Startups like **Snowflake** (traditionally a data platform provider) have even launched **agentic AI offerings for data integration and analysis**, showing how every layer of the stack is incorporating agents ([Microsoft launches sales-focused AI agents | CIO Dive](https://www.ciodive.com/news/microsoft-sales-ai-agent-copilot/741552/#:~:text=Royce)). This crowded field means ServiceNow, Salesforce, and Microsoft must continue to differentiate. So far, each is leaning on its core strength – **ServiceNow on workflow depth, Salesforce on customer data and CRM process, and Microsoft on productivity breadth and integration** – while rapidly encroaching on each other’s territory with partnerships or new features. 

In terms of current maturity: Microsoft’s Copilot is already generally available and making waves in day-to-day productivity (with a price point of ~$30/user/month for enterprise), whereas ServiceNow’s and Salesforce’s agentic platforms are just hitting GA in early 2025 but have strong pilot traction. Microsoft arguably has the lead in **user adoption** (given Office’s reach), Salesforce leads in **CRM-centric AI innovation**, and ServiceNow leads in **operational workflow automation** – but all are converging toward a future where AI agents assist in every aspect of work. The competitive race will likely intensify as each platform expands features and as enterprises evaluate which AI solution delivers the best ROI for their needs.

## Future Forecast 

Looking ahead, we anticipate significant evolution in how ServiceNow and Salesforce advance their AI capabilities, especially in relation to Microsoft 365 Copilot and similar offerings. A few key forecasts and expectations:

- **ServiceNow** will likely transform from an automation platform augmented by AI to an **AI-first orchestration platform**. The acquisitions of Moveworks and Cuein indicate ServiceNow’s intention to offer more **pre-trained, domain-specific agents** (for IT support, HR inquiries, customer service, etc.) that can be deployed quickly. In the near future, we expect ServiceNow to integrate Moveworks’ robust **natural language search** across its platform, allowing its agents to seamlessly pull answers from enterprise knowledge bases or policy documents as they work on tasks ([ServiceNow agentic AI acquisitions set pace for enterprises | TechTarget](https://www.techtarget.com/searchitoperations/news/366620527/ServiceNow-agentic-AI-acquisitions-set-pace-for-enterprises#:~:text=Moveworks%20also%20brings%20AI,18%20months%2C%20according%20to%20ServiceNow)). This will make ServiceNow agents more **knowledgeable and context-aware**, closing the gap on “deep research” capabilities where Microsoft and Salesforce also invest. ServiceNow’s focus on the **AI Agent Orchestrator** hints that it envisions organizations deploying *swarms* of specialized agents that coordinate with each other – for example, a suite of IT agents where one agent monitors for incidents, hands off to another agent for resolution, and a third agent communicates status to users. This kind of multi-agent workflow could become a selling point, especially for large enterprises looking to automate end-to-end processes. By differentiating through out-of-the-box solutions and workflow governance, ServiceNow can compete against Microsoft by saying: “We provide **ready-made enterprise AI agents** that you can trust to follow your complex business rules.” We foresee ServiceNow expanding into **business domains adjacent to its core**, perhaps offering AI agents for finance operations or procurement, leveraging its workflow engine. In competing with Salesforce, ServiceNow might partner more (or integrate) on the customer-facing side – e.g. linking a ServiceNow IT agent with a Salesforce customer service agent for a cohesive service experience – or at least ensure its agents can plug into CRM processes as needed. Overall, expect ServiceNow to continue marketing itself as the **secure and enterprise-specialized AI platform**, possibly touting its adherence to compliance, audit trails, and its success in regulated sectors. In 2-3 years, ServiceNow could become synonymous with “autonomous enterprise workflows,” much as it is today with IT service workflows, if its agentic AI vision materializes.

- **Salesforce** is poised to push the concept of a **“digital workforce” of AI agents** in business. In the next few years, Salesforce will likely integrate Agentforce deeply into every cloud offering – imagine **Salesforce AI agents for sales, service, marketing, commerce, and even integration tasks**. These agents, working collectively, could handle a large portion of routine customer interactions and internal data analysis. Salesforce’s own CEO has described this as *“digital labor” changing how we staff and run businesses* ([Salesforce introduces Agentforce 2.0, unveils pre-built use cases | CIO Dive](https://www.ciodive.com/news/Salesforce-Agentforce2-agentic-AI-platform/735850/#:~:text=Benioff%20said%20during%20the%20event,Tuesday)). Concretely, we might see a scenario where a Salesforce Sales Cloud agent identifies a high-priority lead (from data), a Marketing Cloud agent sends that lead a personalized intro campaign, and a Service Cloud agent is on standby to answer the lead’s questions – all automatically and coordinated through Agentforce. To compete with Microsoft (whose strength is general office productivity), Salesforce will likely emphasize that **customer-facing workflows need specialized AI**. We anticipate Salesforce differentiating by industry as well – offering, say, an **Agentforce package for financial services** that comes pre-loaded with compliance-aware agents for banking scenarios, or for retail, or healthcare. This verticalization is something Salesforce has done with its products historically and is likely to replicate in AI. Moreover, Salesforce’s commitment to an open AI ecosystem (allowing choice of underlying models and focusing on a **trust layer** for security) will remain a key message, especially to win enterprise clients that are concerned about data leakage or model bias. In terms of features, Salesforce agents will become more **action-oriented**: today, an agent might draft an email and recommend an action, but in the future it may autonomously execute multi-step transactions (with human approval checkpoints as needed). Salesforce will have to address the **governance and control** aspect – ensuring AI actions are correct and desired. We expect enhancements in **approval workflows for AI** (letting managers easily review agent-initiated actions) and more sophisticated **feedback loops** so the agents improve over time on company-specific metrics (perhaps through unsupervised learning on interaction outcomes). In competing with ServiceNow’s domain (like IT or HR processes), Salesforce might rely on partners or acquisitions (it has a history of buying companies to fill gaps) – it wouldn’t be surprising if Salesforce acquires or partners closely with an IT operations AI firm to extend Agentforce beyond CRM, thereby encroaching on ServiceNow’s space from the front-office angle. In summary, Salesforce’s future path in AI seems aimed at making AI agents an **indispensable part of every customer interaction and workflow**, selling the vision that companies who embrace this “AI staff” will outcompete those who don’t. 

- **Relative to Microsoft 365 Copilot**, both ServiceNow and Salesforce will carve out competitive niches yet also integrate where necessary. Microsoft’s omnipresence means many enterprises will use Microsoft’s Copilot alongside ServiceNow or Salesforce’s AI. In the future, we might see **hybrid scenarios**: e.g., a manager could ask Microsoft Copilot in Teams to “show open IT tickets and resolve the top 3,” and behind the scenes that triggers ServiceNow’s agents to actually carry out the instructions – essentially Microsoft handling the interface, ServiceNow handling the execution. Likewise, Microsoft’s Sales Agent already demonstrates using Salesforce data ([Microsoft launches sales-focused AI agents | CIO Dive](https://www.ciodive.com/news/microsoft-sales-ai-agent-copilot/741552/#:~:text=,more%20accurate%20and%20actionable%20responses)); in response, Salesforce might ensure Einstein Copilot can pull info from Outlook or Teams to not cede that integration ground. It’s a future of both competition and interoperability. ServiceNow and Salesforce may emphasize **neutrality and multi-cloud support** in their AI offerings (Salesforce already does, highlighting it can use models from various providers and connect to external systems). They could position themselves as *platform-agnostic AI layers* that work with Microsoft’s productivity tools rather than being locked in. On the flip side, Microsoft will likely continue integrating Copilot more deeply into workflows (perhaps even in areas like IT helpdesk via Viva or new offerings) to challenge ServiceNow, and into customer service via Dynamics 365 to challenge Salesforce. 

In forecasting the **enterprise AI landscape**, it’s clear the concept of **agentic AI** – autonomous, goal-driven mini-programs – will become commonplace. Gartner predicts that by 2025, a third of enterprises will have some form of agentic AI in mainstream use ([12 Agentic AI Predictions for 2025 - What's the future of AI? - Atera](https://www.atera.com/blog/agentic-ai-predictions/#:~:text=Atera%20www,furthering%20our%20suspicion%20that)), and by 2027 agentic AI might be the #1 new tech for improving customer experience ([Agentic AI: The Future of Autonomous AI in Enterprise Strategy](https://syncari.com/blog/agentic-ai-how-autonomous-ai-is-transforming-enterprise-strategy/#:~:text=Agentic%20AI%3A%20The%20Future%20of,)). ServiceNow and Salesforce are on track to be key players enabling that, each likely doubling the number of AI agents (and use cases) they support in the next year ([Salesforce introduces Agentforce 2.0, unveils pre-built use cases | CIO Dive](https://www.ciodive.com/news/Salesforce-Agentforce2-agentic-AI-platform/735850/#:~:text=The%20potential%20applications%20span%20industries,quarter%20of%20enterprise%20breaches)). We expect **intense competition on who delivers measurable ROI**: enterprises will favor the platform that can demonstrably save costs or increase revenue via AI. Salesforce’s claim will be revenue growth and customer satisfaction via AI-driven personalization; ServiceNow’s claim will be cost savings and efficiency via AI-driven automation (for example, early adopters like General Mills cited millions in savings due to AI ([ServiceNow releases no-code, low-code AI agent builder | CIO Dive](https://www.ciodive.com/news/servicenow-yokohama-agentic-ai-low-code-development-tool/742275/#:~:text=))). Microsoft will claim both, across the breadth of work. Ultimately, enterprises might use **a combination**: Microsoft for productivity, Salesforce for CRM, ServiceNow for operations – each AI agent network possibly talking to the others. 

In the long run, the competitive differentiator may shift from **capabilities to trust and governance**. All three companies are likely to heavily invest in **AI safety, audits, compliance certifications, and transparent controls** to address the risks of autonomous AI. Those that can convince CIOs and CEOs that their AI won’t go rogue – instead, it will act as a reliable “employee” – will gain an edge. For instance, if ServiceNow can prove its agents reduce security incidents (not cause them) or if Salesforce can show its AI handles customer data in a compliant way out-of-the-box, this reassurance will be critical for widespread adoption. 

In summary, we forecast ServiceNow and Salesforce will aggressively evolve their AI platforms with more autonomous capabilities, taking on more complex tasks and integrating more deeply into organizational ecosystems. They will both compete with Microsoft 365 Copilot by highlighting areas where they excel (workflow and CRM, respectively) and by ensuring their AI can interoperate with Microsoft’s. By 2-3 years from now, the lines between these platforms may blur – one might use Microsoft Copilot to chat with a Salesforce agent about ServiceNow records – but each vendor will strive to be the **primary orchestrator of agentic AI** in the enterprise. The race has just begun, but it’s clear that **AI agents are set to become as ubiquitous as cloud services in the enterprise**, and ServiceNow, Salesforce, and Microsoft are positioning themselves to lead in that agent-driven future.

## Industry Trends and Expert Opinions 

The rise of agentic AI in enterprise software is a top trend backed by industry research and thought leaders. **Analyst firms and surveys** reveal an overwhelming expectation that autonomous AI agents will play a major role in the near future of work. Gartner named “Agentic AI” as the #1 strategic tech trend for 2025, projecting that **by 2025, a significant portion of enterprise software will include agentic AI capabilities** ([Why is There So Much Hype Around AI Agents in 2025? - InnoLead](https://www.innovationleader.com/topics/articles-and-content-by-topic/scouting-trends-and-tech/why-is-there-so-much-hype-around-agentic-ai-2025/#:~:text=Taking%20the%20big%20consultancies%E2%80%99%20perspective,of%20their%20companies%E2%80%99%20AI%20transformation)). McKinsey likewise describes autonomous agents as the next frontier of generative AI in business ([Why is There So Much Hype Around AI Agents in 2025? - InnoLead](https://www.innovationleader.com/topics/articles-and-content-by-topic/scouting-trends-and-tech/why-is-there-so-much-hype-around-agentic-ai-2025/#:~:text=Taking%20the%20big%20consultancies%E2%80%99%20perspective,of%20their%20companies%E2%80%99%20AI%20transformation)). A Boston Consulting Group (BCG) study found **67% of executives anticipate autonomous agents will be part of their AI transformation** ([Why is There So Much Hype Around AI Agents in 2025? - InnoLead](https://www.innovationleader.com/topics/articles-and-content-by-topic/scouting-trends-and-tech/why-is-there-so-much-hype-around-agentic-ai-2025/#:~:text=Taking%20the%20big%20consultancies%E2%80%99%20perspective,of%20their%20companies%E2%80%99%20AI%20transformation)). Further quantifying this momentum, a Capgemini survey of 1,100 large enterprises reported **82% of executives plan to deploy AI agents within the next three years**, even though only about 10% have done so to date ([ServiceNow agentic AI acquisitions set pace for enterprises | TechTarget](https://www.techtarget.com/searchitoperations/news/366620527/ServiceNow-agentic-AI-acquisitions-set-pace-for-enterprises#:~:text=That%20said%2C%20agentic%20AI%20adoption,inaccurate%20or%20even%20unsafe%20responses)). This massive planned adoption indicates that what is today an emerging technology could be mainstream by 2025–2026.

Enterprise leaders are drawn by potential productivity gains. In a July 2024 Capgemini report, more than **4 in 5 executives** expressed intent to integrate AI agents, seeing them as key to faster ROI on AI investments ([Microsoft readies Copilot Studio for agentic AI | CIO Dive](https://www.ciodive.com/news/Microsoft-Copilot-Studio-AI-agents-Ignite-conference/733352/#:~:text=While%20analysts%20are%20still%20questioning,to%20a%20July%20Capgemini%20survey)). A separate survey by Tray.io in 2025 found **over 40% of enterprises planned to build 100+ AI agent prototypes in the next year**, with most believing agents will become core to operations and could handle over 25% of business processes by year-end ([Microsoft launches sales-focused AI agents | CIO Dive](https://www.ciodive.com/news/microsoft-sales-ai-agent-copilot/741552/#:~:text=Enterprises%20have%20expressed%20interest%20in,quarter%20of%20processes)). These prototypes are often targeting IT service desks, data processing, and software development tasks initially ([ServiceNow releases no-code, low-code AI agent builder | CIO Dive](https://www.ciodive.com/news/servicenow-yokohama-agentic-ai-low-code-development-tool/742275/#:~:text=More%20than%202%20in%205,Many%20were%20prioritizing%20cost%20reductions)). As **Andy Thurai, an analyst at Constellation Research**, observed, making generative AI *operationally viable* via agents is seen as the way to finally realize ROI from the AI hype of recent years ([ServiceNow agentic AI acquisitions set pace for enterprises | TechTarget](https://www.techtarget.com/searchitoperations/news/366620527/ServiceNow-agentic-AI-acquisitions-set-pace-for-enterprises#:~:text=Agentic%20AI%2C%20in%20which%20sets,own%20AI%20models%20in%20production)). Early case studies support this: **Toyota** has been building a system of generative AI agents (9 agents in use) to help store and share knowledge internally ([Microsoft readies Copilot Studio for agentic AI | CIO Dive](https://www.ciodive.com/news/Microsoft-Copilot-Studio-AI-agents-Ignite-conference/733352/#:~:text=capabilities%2C%20businesses%20are%20engaged,to%20a%20July%20Capgemini%20survey)), and companies like FedEx and Saks have dived into Salesforce’s Agentforce, seeing “digital co-workers” as a productivity boon ([Salesforce introduces Agentforce 2.0, unveils pre-built use cases | CIO Dive](https://www.ciodive.com/news/Salesforce-Agentforce2-agentic-AI-platform/735850/#:~:text=to%20a%20July%20Capgemini%20survey)).

At the same time, **experts caution about challenges and risks**. **Avivah Litan, Gartner analyst**, noted that introducing agents “gets even more complicated,” warning that by 2028 about **25% of enterprise breaches will be traced back to AI agent abuse** if proper security isn’t in place ([Microsoft readies Copilot Studio for agentic AI | CIO Dive](https://www.ciodive.com/news/Microsoft-Copilot-Studio-AI-agents-Ignite-conference/733352/#:~:text=%E2%80%9CWhen%20you%20introduce%20agents%2C%20it,in%20a%20mature%20security%20environment)). This concern is echoed widely: CIOs are mindful that while agents can act independently, they need guardrails. **Gartner’s prediction** of one-quarter of breaches from AI agents ([Salesforce introduces Agentforce 2.0, unveils pre-built use cases | CIO Dive](https://www.ciodive.com/news/Salesforce-Agentforce2-agentic-AI-platform/735850/#:~:text=The%20potential%20applications%20span%20industries,quarter%20of%20enterprise%20breaches)) has put a spotlight on the need for robust **governance, identity and access management for AI, and monitoring of agent decisions**. **Executives from KPMG** have said their experiments with AI agents remain in pilot stage specifically because they are first focusing on “identifying and instilling the necessary guardrails” before scaling up ([Microsoft readies Copilot Studio for agentic AI | CIO Dive](https://www.ciodive.com/news/Microsoft-Copilot-Studio-AI-agents-Ignite-conference/733352/#:~:text=security%20environment)). Ensuring that agents follow compliance rules, don’t expose sensitive data, and handle exceptions correctly will be crucial to successful deployments.

There’s also the **human factor**. Surveys highlight a mix of enthusiasm and anxiety among employees. In a 2025 SnapLogic survey, **85% of IT decision-makers said they trust AI agents to perform tasks as well as or better than humans** ([ServiceNow releases no-code, low-code AI agent builder | CIO Dive](https://www.ciodive.com/news/servicenow-yokohama-agentic-ai-low-code-development-tool/742275/#:~:text=AI%20agents%20%E2%80%94%20and%20address,makers%27%20concerns)). Workers see the upside of offloading drudgery: these agents can take on mundane tasks, allowing people to focus on higher-level work. However, a Pegasystems study found **2 in 5 employees feel uncomfortable submitting AI-generated work as their own** ([ServiceNow releases no-code, low-code AI agent builder | CIO Dive](https://www.ciodive.com/news/servicenow-yokohama-agentic-ai-low-code-development-tool/742275/#:~:text=While%20workers%20are%20receptive%20to,according%20to%20a%20Pegasystems%20survey)), and question the accuracy and quality of AI outputs. This underscores that while agentic AI can boost efficiency, organizations must manage acceptance – through training, transparency (showing sources or rationale for agent decisions), and perhaps redefining job roles to clarify how humans supervise or collaborate with AI agents. **Marc Benioff (CEO of Salesforce)** often speaks about “trust” in AI; Salesforce’s introduction of the Einstein Trust Layer is one industry response to quell fears by ensuring data privacy and allowing users to see why an AI answered a certain way. 

Industry observers also point out a shift in narrative: **“AI assistants” vs “AI agents.”** We’ve moved from talking about simple chatbots to autonomous agents that can drive outcomes. As one commentator humorously noted, Salesforce’s marketing (with Hollywood actors in ads) implies if you’re not embracing AI agents, you’ll be left behind ([Why is There So Much Hype Around AI Agents in 2025? - InnoLead](https://www.innovationleader.com/topics/articles-and-content-by-topic/scouting-trends-and-tech/why-is-there-so-much-hype-around-agentic-ai-2025/#:~:text=One%20ad%20in%20particular%20was,miss%20your%20flight%20to%20the)). It’s not just hype – it reflects a genuine belief that agentic AI is the path to the next big leap in productivity. **Adam Evans, Salesforce’s Head of AI**, said that to break through current productivity plateaus, we need agents that **“can be proactive” rather than just reactive assistants ([Salesforce introduces Agentforce 2.0, unveils pre-built use cases | CIO Dive](https://www.ciodive.com/news/Salesforce-Agentforce2-agentic-AI-platform/735850/#:~:text=%E2%80%9CWhat%20we%20need%20to%20really,%E2%80%9D)).** This sentiment is shared across the industry: agents should eventually initiate helpful actions on their own. 

Another trend is the **growing ecosystem and investment around enterprise AI agents**. Venture capital in late 2024 has been pouring into startups building domain-specific agents ([Why is There So Much Hype Around AI Agents in 2025? - InnoLead](https://www.innovationleader.com/topics/articles-and-content-by-topic/scouting-trends-and-tech/why-is-there-so-much-hype-around-agentic-ai-2025/#:~:text=In%20terms%20of%20venture%20capital,ai%20%28software%20development%29%2C%20or)). Many smaller companies are tackling niches: AI agents for customer support, for marketing optimization, for IT ops (some of which bigger players like ServiceNow then acquire). **Forrester’s finding of ~400 vendors with agent platforms** illustrates the Cambrian explosion of solutions ([ServiceNow adds agentic capabilities, thousands of pre-built AI agents | CIO Dive](https://www.ciodive.com/news/ServiceNow-AI-agent-portfolio-enterprise-automation/738685/#:~:text=Salesforce%20is%20adding%202%2C000%20sales,the%20degree%20of%20autonomy%20varies)). This indicates innovation is not only coming from the giants; often new features (like a novel way to chain agents or a breakthrough in reducing hallucinations) come from startups, which then get integrated into larger platforms. Enterprise software leaders are keeping a close eye on these innovators. In fact, ServiceNow’s acquisition of Cuein was noteworthy partially because **Salesforce was also an investor** ([HOT TAKE: ServiceNow Hits the Gas on Agentic AI Roadmap with Cuein AI Pick Up | Constellation Research Inc.](https://www.constellationr.com/blog-news/hot-take-servicenow-hits-gas-agentic-ai-roadmap-cuein-ai-pick#:~:text=What%20we%20know%20about%20the,so%20it)) – it shows how competitive it is to grab valuable AI tech and talent.

**Expert opinions** also emphasize the **compute and infrastructure demands** of agentic AI. Running multiple agents that can operate continuously and handle rich data requires serious computing power. Cloud providers (Microsoft, Google, AWS) are all developing specialized hardware to handle AI workloads. Microsoft, for example, announced custom Azure chips to help run agentic AI with better security and efficiency ([Microsoft readies Copilot Studio for agentic AI | CIO Dive](https://www.ciodive.com/news/Microsoft-Copilot-Studio-AI-agents-Ignite-conference/733352/#:~:text=Infusing%20agentic%20AI%20throughout%20operations,to%20meet%20the%20new%20requirements)) ([Microsoft readies Copilot Studio for agentic AI | CIO Dive](https://www.ciodive.com/news/Microsoft-Copilot-Studio-AI-agents-Ignite-conference/733352/#:~:text=Microsoft%20unveiled%20customized%20chips%20Tuesday,cloud%20infrastructure%2C%20the%20company%20said)). This suggests that the winners in agentic AI might also be those who can effectively deliver the needed performance at scale (which favors companies like Microsoft and Google with deep cloud infrastructure, but Salesforce and ServiceNow partnering with clouds can mitigate that). 

Looking further, some experts foresee the **“AI agent workforce” doubling in the next year** ([Salesforce introduces Agentforce 2.0, unveils pre-built use cases | CIO Dive](https://www.ciodive.com/news/Salesforce-Agentforce2-agentic-AI-platform/735850/#:~:text=The%20potential%20applications%20span%20industries,quarter%20of%20enterprise%20breaches)) and then expanding exponentially, potentially leading to new organizational structures. There’s talk of companies managing “teams” composed of human employees and AI agents together. This raises fascinating organizational questions – how do you benchmark an AI agent’s performance, who “manages” the AI, how to handle errors (which might be analogous to employee mistakes)? We’re already seeing early adopters create **AI governance committees** and new roles like “AI product manager” or “prompt engineer” to oversee this integration. **Stephen Elliot, IDC analyst**, remarked on the “massive productivity opportunities” if expert LLMs can answer diverse questions and drive actions, compressing access to data and decisions ([ServiceNow agentic AI acquisitions set pace for enterprises | TechTarget](https://www.techtarget.com/searchitoperations/news/366620527/ServiceNow-agentic-AI-acquisitions-set-pace-for-enterprises#:~:text=,an%20ability%20to%20drive%20actions)). But he also noted companies are under pressure to show **real returns on AI investments** after a period of experimentation ([ServiceNow agentic AI acquisitions set pace for enterprises | TechTarget](https://www.techtarget.com/searchitoperations/news/366620527/ServiceNow-agentic-AI-acquisitions-set-pace-for-enterprises#:~:text=heavy%20workflow%20,Thurai%20said)). This pressure will likely intensify – boards and investors will ask, “we spent on AI, what are we getting back?” Agentic AI is expected to be the answer, delivering tangible automations and cost savings rather than just experimental chatbots.

In conclusion, industry trends and expert voices convey **optimism with caution**. The consensus is that agentic AI is transformative – potentially as significant as past shifts like the internet or mobile – in how work gets done. Enterprises are gearing up to deploy these agents widely, motivated by promises of efficiency, competitive advantage, and new business models. Yet, they heed warnings around security breaches, hallucinations, ethical use, and workforce impact. Leaders like Marc Benioff advocate embracing “digital co-workers” wholeheartedly, while analysts advise implementing strong oversight and starting with pilot programs. The next few years will serve as a learning period across the industry: best practices in agent governance will emerge, as will success stories of dramatic ROI and perhaps high-profile failures where oversight was lacking (which will be instructive). 

One thing is clear: **agentic AI in enterprise software is here to stay**. As an Innovation Lead wrote, this is about “LLMs extending further out into our world to do practical tasks for us – rather than just respond to questions” ([Why is There So Much Hype Around AI Agents in 2025? - InnoLead](https://www.innovationleader.com/topics/articles-and-content-by-topic/scouting-trends-and-tech/why-is-there-so-much-hype-around-agentic-ai-2025/#:~:text=deploying%20them%3F%C2%A0Who%20will%20absorb%20the,more%20practical%20tasks%20for%20us)). In other words, AI is moving from the role of advisor to the role of **autonomous doer**. ServiceNow, Salesforce, and Microsoft are at the forefront of this evolution. Their investments and roadmaps, coupled with industry enthusiasm, suggest that in the very near future, it will be normal for an employee to have AI agents as part of their team – handling everything from research to execution. The enterprises that harness these agentic AI capabilities effectively (and responsibly) are poised to leap ahead, while those that delay may find themselves, as Salesforce’s ad humorously hinted, “running to catch the flight” they’re about to miss ([Why is There So Much Hype Around AI Agents in 2025? - InnoLead](https://www.innovationleader.com/topics/articles-and-content-by-topic/scouting-trends-and-tech/why-is-there-so-much-hype-around-agentic-ai-2025/#:~:text=One%20ad%20in%20particular%20was,miss%20your%20flight%20to%20the)). 

